{"title_page": "Star-Club", "text_new": "{{Hatnote|For the Japanese punk band, see [[The Star Club]]. For the British rock band, see [[Starclub]]}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2010}}\n[[File:STAR-CLUB Eingang Hamburg 1968.jpg|right|thumb|Entrance to the Star-Club, Hamburg. 1968.]]\nThe '''Star-Club''' was a music club in [[Hamburg]], [[Germany]], that opened on Friday 13 April 1962, and was initially operated by Manfred Weissleder and [[Horst Fascher]]. In the 1960s, many of the giants of [[rock music]] played at the club.  The club closed on 31 December 1969 and the building it occupied was destroyed by a fire in 1987. The address of the club was ''Gro\u00dfe Freiheit 39'' in the [[St. Pauli]] quarter of Hamburg. ''[[Gro\u00dfe Freiheit]]'' is a side street of the [[Reeperbahn]].\n\nThe club achieved worldwide renown through the performances of [[The Beatles]], who played there 13 April \u2014 31 May, 1\u201414 November, and 18\u201431 December 1962. A performance or parts of several performances from the end of the latter stay was or were recorded on a home [[tape recorder|tape machine]], and a remixed version was released in 1977 as ''[[Live! at the Star-Club in Hamburg, Germany; 1962]]''.\n\nThe Beatles' first Hamburg Club performance was at the [[The Beatles in Hamburg#The Indra and Kaiserkeller|Indra Club]] (also on Gro\u00dfe Freiheit) on 17 August 1960.\n\n==Musicians who played at Star-Club==\n[[File:Star club gedenkstein.jpg|thumb|The Star-Club memorial in St. Pauli, Germany.]]\nList of musicians who played in the Star-Club:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.center-of-beat.com/starclub/bands/starclub_bands.php |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-01-17 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708132638/http://www.center-of-beat.com/starclub/bands/starclub_bands.php |archive-date=2011-07-08 |df= }} List of musicians who played in the Star-Club</ref> \n* American musicians:\n**[[Ray Charles]]\n**[[Bo Diddley]]\n**[[Fats Domino]]\n**[[Everly Brothers]]\n**[[Bill Haley (musician)|Bill Haley]]\n**[[Jimi Hendrix]]\n**[[Johnny and the Hurricanes]]\n**[[Brenda Lee]]\n**[[Jerry Lee Lewis]] (who released a highly praised [[Live at the Star Club, Hamburg|live album]] recorded at the club in 1964)\n**[[Little Richard]], who at that point had [[Billy Preston]] in his band\n**[[The Monks]], with [[Gary Burger]], Eddie Shaw, Dave Day, Roger Johnston and Larry Clark played at the Top Ten Club a number of time 1965, 1966, and 1967.<ref>Book, Black Monk Time</ref>\n* English musicians:\n**[[The Beatles]]\n**[[Cliff Bennett and the Rebel Rousers]]\n**[[The Big Three (English band)|The Big Three]]\n**[[Black Sabbath]]\n**[[Chicken Shack]], featuring [[Christine McVie]]\n**[[Cream (band)|Cream]]\n**[[Lee Curtis and the All-Stars]]\n**[[Dave Dee, Dozy, Beaky, Mick & Tich]]\n**[[Earth (British band)|Earth]] (pre-[[Black Sabbath]])\n**The Graduates\n**[[Gun (1960s band)|Gun]]\n**[[The Jimi Hendrix Experience]] (US/UK, March 1967)\n**The Jaybirds, featuring [[Alvin Lee]], Leo Lyons and Pete Evans.\n**[[Innocent Child]] - Blackpool Rock Band (originally Cherry Blossom Clinic)  \n**[[Billy J. Kramer]]\n**[[The Dakotas (band)|The Dakotas]]\n**[[The Liverbirds]]\n**The Londoners\n**[[The Overlanders (band)|The Overlanders]]\n**[[The Pretty Things]]\n**[[The Remo Four]]\n**[[The Searchers (band)|The Searchers]]\n**[[Kingsize Taylor and the Dominoes]]\n**[[Richard Thompson (musician)|Richard Thompson]]\n**[[Soft Machine]]\n**[[The Twilights]]\n**Tony Vincent and The Giants\n**Jane Cane (jazz singer)\n**[[The Roadrunners]] \u2014 Liverpool's original R & B band of the 60s\n**Katch 22 \u2014 London band formed in 1966\n**Terry Slater and The Flintstones\n**The Undertakers(Band) German musicians: [[The Rattles]] and many more\nCasey Jones & The Governors \n* Italian musicians: \n**Benjamin & His Brothers - Rock 'n' Roll band featuring [[Mino Reitano]]\n* Swedish musician:\n**[[Jerry Williams (singer)|Jerry Williams]]\n\n==Star-Club Records==\nIn October 1962, Siegfried Loch, label manager for [[Philips Records]], visited the Star-Club for a concert with [[Fats Domino]]. Loch persuaded Manfred Weissleder, the manager of Star-Club, to give him permission to set up recording equipment in the club.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://recordcollectormag.com/articles/beatles-star-club-recordings-reel-story|title=The Beatles' Star Club Recordings The Reel Story - Record Collector Magazine|last=|first=|date=|website=recordcollectormag.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref> He started a record label, ''Star-Club Records'', subsidiary of Philips Records.\n\n{{Portal|1960s}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Star-Club}} \n*http://www.center-of-beat.com/ Information about the Star-Club\n*http://www.starclub-hamburg.eu/ Information about the Star-Club\n*http://www.merseycats.com/Maja's-Memories-of-the-Star-Club.html Reminisce to the opening of the Star-Club, with an original recording of the Beatles (\"[[A Taste of Honey (song)|A Taste of Honey]]\")\n*http://beatles.ncf.ca/starclubtapes.html Eric Krasker, The Star-Club tapes : The set that never existed.\n\n{{The Beatles main}}\n\n{{coord|53|33|04|N|9|57|28|E|display=title|region:DE-HH_type:landmark_source:dewiki}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Star-Club}}\n[[Category:Nightclubs in Hamburg]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Hamburg-Mitte]]\n[[Category:Music venues in Germany]]\n[[Category:Former music venues in Germany]]\n[[Category:Culture in Hamburg]]\n[[Category:20th century in Hamburg]]\n[[Category:Music venues completed in 1962]]\n[[Category:1962 establishments in West Germany]]\n[[Category:1969 disestablishments]]\n", "text_old": "{{Hatnote|For the Japanese punk band, see [[The Star Club]]. For the British rock band, see [[Starclub]]}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2010}}\n[[File:STAR-CLUB Eingang Hamburg 1968.jpg|right|thumb|Entrance to the Star-Club, Hamburg. 1968.]]\nThe '''Star-Club''' wa