ton, Greenfield and Pulloxhill, Flitwick East, Flitwick West, Harlington, Houghton, Haynes, Southill and Old Warden, Marston, Maulden and Clophill, Shefford, Campton and Gravenhurst, Shillington, Stondon and Henlow Camp, Streatley, Silsoe, Toddington, Westoning and Tingrith.\n|[[Image:MidBedfordshire2007Constituency.svg|left|100px|alt=A large constituency, occupying the centre of the county.]]\n|-\n|[[North East Bedfordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|North East Bedfordshire]] CC\n|90,679\n|24,283\n| bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |&nbsp;\n|[[Richard Fuller (Bedford MP)|Richard Fuller]] \u2020\n| bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |&nbsp;\n|Julian Vaughan\t\u2021\n|[[Bedford Borough Council]]: Bromham, Carlton, Clapham, Eastcotts, Great Barford, Harrold, Oakley, Riseley, Roxton, Sharnbrook. [[Central Bedfordshire Council]]: Arlesey, Biggleswade Holme, Biggleswade Ivel, Biggleswade Stratton, Langford and Henlow Village, Northill and Blunham, Potton and Wensley, Sandy Ivel, Sandy Pinnacle, Stotfold.\n|[[Image:NorthEastBedfordshire2007Constituency.svg|left|100px|alt=A large constituency in the north of the county.]]\n|-\n|[[South West Bedfordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|South West Bedfordshire]] CC\n|79,926\n|18,583\n| bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |&nbsp;\n|[[Andrew Selous]] \u2020\n| bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |&nbsp;\n|Callum Anderson \u2021\n|[[Central Bedfordshire Council]]: All Saints, Chiltern, Dunstable Central, Eaton Bray, Grovebury, Heath and Reach, Houghton Hall, Icknield, Kensworth and Totternhoe, Linslade, Manshead, Northfields, Parkside, Planets, Plantation, Southcott, Stanbridge, Tithe Farm, Watling.\n|[[Image:SouthWestBedfordshire2007Constituency.svg|left|100px|alt=A medium constituency in the southwest of the county.]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==History of Constituencies and Boundaries==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Constituency\n!1295-1885\n!1885-1918\n!1918-1950\n!1950-1974\n!1974-1983\n!1983-1997\n!1997-present\n|-\n|[[Bedford (UK Parliament constituency)|Bedford]]\n| align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#f781f3\" colspan=5|1295-1983\n|\n| bgcolor=\"#f781f3\" |1997-present\n|-\n|[[Bedfordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Bedfordshire]]\n| bgcolor=\"#99ff99\" |1295-1885\n| colspan=6|\n|-\n|[[Biggleswade (UK Parliament constituency)|Biggleswade]]\n|\n| bgcolor=\"#99ff99\" |1885-1918\n| colspan=5|\n|-\n|[[Luton (UK Parliament constituency)|Luton]]\n|\n| align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#99ff99\" colspan=3|1885-1974\n| colspan=3|\n|-\n|[[Luton East (UK Parliament constituency)|Luton East]]\n| colspan=4|\n| bgcolor=\"#99ff99\" |1974-1983\n| colspan=2|\n|-\n|[[Luton North (UK Parliament constituency)|Luton North]]\n| colspan=5|\n| align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#f781f3\" colspan=2|1983-present\n|-\n|[[Luton South (UK Parliament constituency)|Luton South]]\n| colspan=5|\n| align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#f781f3\" colspan=2|1983-present\n|-\n|[[Luton West (UK Parliament constituency)|Luton West]]\n| colspan=4|\n| bgcolor=\"#99ff99\" |1974-1983\n| colspan=2|\n|-\n|[[Mid Bedfordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Mid Bedfordshire]]\n| colspan=2|\n| align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#f781f3\" colspan=5|1918-present\n|-\n|[[North Bedfordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|North Bedfordshire]]\n| colspan=5|\n| bgcolor=\"#99ff99\" |1983-1997\n|\n|-\n|[[North East Bedfordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|North East Bedfordshire]]\n| colspan=6|\n| align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#f781f3\" |1997-present\n|-\n|[[South Bedfordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|South Bedfordshire]]\n| colspan=3|\n| align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#f781f3\" colspan=4|1950-present\n|-\n|[[South West Bedfordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|South West Bedfordshire]]\n| colspan=5|\n| align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#f781f3\" colspan=2|1983-present\n|}\n\n==== Prior to 1885 ====\n1295 to 1885: [[Bedfordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Bedfordshire]] as with all other English counties, elected 2 MPs to the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] per the freehold property franchise; and the Parliamentary Borough of [[Bedford (UK Parliament constituency)|Bedford]] returned 2 MPs.  The [[Reform Act 1832|Great Reform Act]] of 1832 changed the setup nationally, but this was one of the few counties totally unaffected.\n\n==== 1885-1918 ====\nUnder the [[Redistribution of Seats Act 1885]], the County was divided into 2 seats:\n*the Northern or [[Biggleswade (UK Parliament constituency)|Biggleswade]] Division (often written North Beds); and \n*the Southern or [[Luton (UK Parliament constituency)|Luton]] Division (often written South Beds)  \n\nBiggleswade covered the northern half of the county including Ampthill and Kempston. It also welcomed votes from non-resident freeholders of the Municipal Borough of Bedford.  Luton covered the southern half of the county, including Leighton Buzzard and the Municipal Boroughs of Dunstable and Luton. \n\n*Bedford was kept as a Parliamentary Borough but reduced to 1 MP.\n\n==== 1918-1950 ====\nUnder the [[Representation of the People Act 1918]], the Parliamentary Borough was technically abolished.  The Municipal Borough was now included in a Bedford seat/Division of the county taking in the Urban District of Kempston and the rural areas of the northern part of the abolished North Beds; the southern areas of which, including the Urban Districts of Biggleswade and Ampthill made a [[Mid Bedfordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Mid Bedfordshire]] Division, along with Leighton Buzzard and surrounding rural areas transferred from Luton.\n\n==== 1950-1974 ====\nThe [[Representation of the People Act 1948]] resumed the pre-1885 net total of 4 MPs. It created a \"South Bedfordshire\" seat of Dunstable with the Leagrave and Limbury parts of the Municipal Borough of Luton, from abolished Luton/South Beds, and Leighton Buzzard, from \"Mid Bedfordshire\".  \"Luton\" was created, a Borough Constituency, for the Municipal Borough save the mentioned parts.  Mid Bedfordshire gained southern and eastern rural areas from \"Bedford\".\n\n==== 1974-1983 ====\nThe county limits altered: South Bedfordshire gained the former Urban District of Linslade in Buckinghamshire which had been merged with that of Leighton Buzzard to form the Urban District of Leighton-Linslade; and Mid Bedfordshire lost the village of Eaton Socon taken into the Urban District of St Neots in Huntingdonshire.\n\nThe Second Review resulted in an increase to 5 MPs. Luton was abolished to create Borough Constituencies of [[Luton East (UK Parliament constituency)|Luton East]] and [[Luton West (UK Parliament constituency)|West]].  The majority of the latter comprised the Leagrave and Limbury districts, taken from South Bedfordshire.  \n\n==== 1983-1997 ====\nThe Third Periodic Review left the county's representation at 5 MPs, but saw significant changes, retaining only Mid Bedfordshire.  Bedford was abolished, being largely replaced by [[North Bedfordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|North Bedfordshire]] save for Kempston, transferred to Mid Bedfordshire.  Luton East and Luton West were replaced by [[Luton South (UK Parliament constituency)|Luton South]] and [[Luton North (UK Parliament constituency)|Luton North]] respectively, with both taking small parts of South Bedfordshire, with Luton North extending further north to include Flitwick that had been in Mid Bedfordshire.  South Bedfordshire was abolished and largely replaced by [[South West Bedfordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|South West Bedfordshire]], which  took in south-western parts of Mid Bedfordshire.\n\n==== 1997-2010 ====\nThe Fourth Review resulted in an increase to 6 MPs.  Bedford was re-established as a Borough Constituency comprising the town of Bedford itself, which had constituted the majority of the abolished constituency of North Bedfordshire, and Kempston which was transferred back from Mid Bedfordshire. A new County Constituency of [[North East Bedfordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|North East Bedfordshire]] was created, comprising the remaining (rural) areas of North Bedfordshire and northern and eastern parts of Mid Bedfordshire seeing about half its electorate lost including Biggleswade and Sandy.  To compensate for this and the loss of Kempston, Mid Bedfordshire regained the areas previously transferred to South West Bedfordshire and gained the parts outside the Borough of Luton from North Luton (including Flitwick).  The latter became a Borough Constituency and gained the Saints ward from Luton South.\n\n==== 2010-present ====\n[[Fifth Periodic Review of Westminster constituencies|Fifth Review]] - marginal changes due to revision of local authority wards.\n\n{| border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"2\" \n|-\n! bgcolor=\"#ff9999\" |Name!! bgcolor=\"#ff9999\" |Pre-2010 Boundaries!! bgcolor=\"#ff9999\" |Post-2010 Boundaries\n|-\n|\n#[[Bedford (UK Parliament constituency)|Bedford BC]]\n#[[Luton North (UK Parliament constituency)|Luton North BC]]\n#[[Luton South (UK Parliament constituency)|Luton South BC]]\n#[[Mid Bedfordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Mid Bedfordshire CC]]\n#[[North East Bedfordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|North East Bedfordshire CC]]\n#[[South West Bedfordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|South West Bedfordshire CC]]\n|[[Image:BedfordshireParliamentaryConstituenciesNumbered.svg|left|Parliamentary constituencies in Bedfordshire 1997 - 2005]]\n|[[Image:BedfordshireParliamentaryConstituencies2007.svg|left|Parliamentary constituencies in Bedfordshire 2010 - present]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==Changes proposed in 2018==\nThe [[Boundary Commission for England]] submitted their final proposals in respect of the [[Sixth Periodic Review of Westminster constituencies|Sixth Periodic Review of Westminster Constituencies]] (the 2018 review) in September 2018. The proposals were immediately laid before [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]] they were not timetabled by the [[Government of the United Kingdom|Government]] for approval. They were thus ignored for the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|election on 12 December 2019]].\n\nUnder the [[Parliamentary Voting System and Constituencies Act 2011]], the Review would cut the number of MPs from 650 to 600 and see a revived strictness of avoiding [[malapportionment]] (electoral parity rule) that the electorate of all seats must be within 5% of the electoral (average national) quota (number of electors). The review was carried out using the official UK electorate figures for 2015 thus quota found to be 74,769, establishing a range of 71,031 to 78,507.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bce2018.org.uk/publications|title=Final recommendations report|last=Boundary Commission for England, 2018 Review, Associated consultation documents|date=September 2018|access-date=2019-02-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190215215741/https://www.bce2018.org.uk/publications|archive-date=2019-02-15|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nTo meet this the Commission was able to treat Bedfordshire as a sub-region of the Eastern Region and recommended that the county retained six seats.  [[Luton South (UK Parliament constituency)|Luton South]] would gain the remainder of the [[Central Bedfordshire]] ward of [[Caddington]] from [[South West Bedfordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|South West Bedfordshire]] and the [[Luton|Borough of Luton]] ward of [[Barnfield, Luton|Barnfield]] from [[Luton North (UK Parliament constituency)|Luton North]]. In turn, Luton North would gain three wards from South West Bedfordshire comprising the town of [[Houghton Regis]]. In recognition of this the name of this seat is to be/would be '''Luton North and Houghton Regis'''.  The separator of South West Bedfordshire from [[Mid Bedfordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Mid Bedfordshire]] would be moved northwards again and limits around the town of [[Bedford]] affecting the seats of [[Bedford (UK Parliament constituency)|Bedford]], [[North East Bedfordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|North East Bedfordshire]] and Mid Bedfordshire would be adjusted to take account of the revision of wards in the [[Borough of Bedford]] and updated electorate (eligible adults to vote) figures.<ref name=\":0\" />\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|'''Current  constituencies'''\n|'''Electorate'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bce2018.org.uk/publications|title=The electorate of each region subdivided by both local authorities and each existing constituency|last=Boundary Commission for England, 2018 Review, Associated consultation documents (Document type: Electoral data)|date=24 February 2016|access-date=17 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190215215741/https://www.bce2018.org.uk/publications|archive-date=15 February 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|'''Proposed  constituencies'''<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bce2018.org.uk/publications|title=Final recommendations constituency list (with wards)|last=Boundary Commission for England, 2018 Review, Associated consultation documents|date=September 2018|access-date=2019-02-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190215215741/https://www.bce2018.org.uk/publications|archive-date=2019-02-15|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|'''Electorate'''<ref name=\":1\" />\n|-\n|[[Bedford (UK Parliament constituency)|Bedford]] BC\n|70,259\n|Bedford BC\n|74,520\n|-\n|[[Luton North (UK Parliament constituency)|Luton North]] BC\n|64,552\n|Luton North and Houghton Regis BC\n|71,188\n|-\n|[[Luton South (UK Parliament constituency)|Luton South]] BC\n|64,136\n|Luton South BC\n|71,881\n|-\n|[[Mid Bedfordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Mid Bedfordshire]] CC\n|80,069\n|Mid Bedfordshire CC\n|74,088\n|-\n|[[North East Bedfordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|North East Bedfordshire]] CC\n|83,599\n|North East Bedfordshire CC\n|74,198\n|-\n|[[South West Bedfordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|South West Bedfordshire]] CC\n|76,959\n|South West Bedfordshire CC\n|73,699\n|-\n|\n|'''439,574'''\n|\n|'''439,574'''