ituencies in the county.]]\n|-\n|[[Reading East (UK Parliament constituency)|Reading East BC]]\n|77,465\n|5,924\n| bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |&nbsp;\n|[[Matt Rodda]] \u2021\n| bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n|Craig Morley \u2020\n|\n|[[File:ReadingEastConstituency.svg|left|100px|alt=A medium-to-large constituency, located in the southeast of the county.]]\n|-\n|[[Reading West (UK Parliament constituency)|Reading West CC]]\n|74,623\n|4,117\n| bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n|[[Alok Sharma]] \u2020\n| bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n|Rachel Eden \u2021\n|\n|[[File:ReadingWestConstituency.svg|left|100px|alt=A small constituency, located in the centre of the county, to the east of two other small constituencies.]]\n|-\n|[[Slough (UK Parliament constituency)|Slough BC]]\n|87,632\n|13,640\n| bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n|[[Tan Dhesi]] \u2021\n| bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n|Kanwal Toor Gill \u2020\n|\n|[[File:SloughConstituency.svg|left|100px|alt=A small constituency, located in the centre of the county to the south of two equally small constituencies.]]\n|-\n|[[Windsor (UK Parliament constituency)|Windsor CC]]\n|75,038\n|20,079\n| bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n|[[Adam Afriyie]] \u2020\n| bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\" |&nbsp;\n|Julian Tisi \u00a4\n|\n|[[File:WindsorConstituency.svg|left|100px|alt=A small constituency, situated in the centre of the county to the west of two similarly-sized constituencies.]]\n|-\n|[[Wokingham (UK Parliament constituency)|Wokingham CC]]\n|83,953\n|7,383\n| bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n|[[John Redwood]] \u2020\n| bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\" |&nbsp;\n|[[Phillip Lee (British politician)|Dr Phillip Lee]] \u00a4\n|\n|[[File:WokinghamConstituency.svg|left|100px|alt=A small constituency, situated in the centre of the county to the west of two similarly-sized constituencies.]]\n|-\n|}\n\n== History of constituencies and boundaries ==\n\n==== Prior to 1832 ====\nSince 1295, the Parliamentary County of [[Berkshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Berkshire]], along with all other English Counties regardless of size or population, had elected 2 MPs to the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] in accordance with the freehold property franchise.  The county also included the Parliamentary Boroughs of [[Reading (UK Parliament constituency)|Reading]], [[Wallingford (UK Parliament constituency)|Wallingford]] and [[Windsor (UK Parliament constituency)|New Windsor]] each returning 2 MPs and [[Abingdon (UK Parliament constituency)|Abingdon]] (which was partly in Oxfordshire) which returned 1 MP (one of only a handful of English Boroughs to do so).\n\n==== 1832-1885 ====\nThe [[Reform Act 1832|Great Reform Act]] of 1832 radically changed the representation of the House of Commons. The County's representation was increased to 3 MPs, whilst that of the Borough of Wallingford was reduced to 1 MP.  Under the [[Representation of the People Act 1867|Reform Act of 1867]], the representation of the Borough of New Windsor was also reduced to 1 MP, at the same time expanding its boundaries to include [[Clewer]] and [[Eton, Berkshire|Eton]] (the latter being north of the River Thames in [[Buckinghamshire]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/maps/sheet/bc_reports_1868/New_Windsor_1868|title=H.M.S.O. Boundary Commission Report 1868, New Windsor|website=www.visionofbritain.org.uk|access-date=2019-02-04}}</ref>\n\n==== 1885-1918 ====\nUnder the [[Redistribution of Seats Act 1885]], the County was divided into 3 single-member constituencies, namely the Northern or [[Abingdon (UK Parliament constituency)|Abingdon]] Division, the Southern or [[Newbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Newbury]] Division and the Eastern or [[Wokingham (UK Parliament constituency)|Wokingham]] Division.  The Boroughs of Wallingford and Abingdon were abolished and absorbed into the county Division of Abingdon and Reading had its representation reduced to 1 MP.\n\nThe table shows an approximate representation of the development of constituencies in Berkshire since 1885. The text below gives a more detailed description.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!1885-1918\n!1918-1950\n!1950-1955\n!1955-1974\n!1974-1983\n!1983-1997\n!1997\u2013present\n|-\n|[[Abingdon (UK Parliament constituency)|Abingdon CC]]\n|Abingdon CC\n|Abingdon CC\n|Abingdon CC\n|Abingdon CC\n| colspan=\"2\" |''Transferred to Oxfordshire''\n''([[Wantage (UK Parliament constituency)|Wantage CC]] and [[Oxford West and Abingdon (UK Parliament constituency)|Oxford West and Abingdon]] CC)''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Reading (UK Parliament constituency)|Reading BC]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Reading BC\n|[[Reading North (UK Parliament constituency)|Reading North BC]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Reading BC\n|Reading North BC\n|[[Reading West (UK Parliament constituency)|Reading West CC]]\n|Reading West CC\n|-\n|[[Reading South (UK Parliament constituency)|Reading South BC]]\n|Reading South CC\n|[[Reading East (UK Parliament constituency)|Reading East CC]]\n|Reading East BC\n|-\n|[[Newbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Newbury CC]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Newbury CC\n|Newbury CC\n|Newbury CC\n|Newbury CC\n|Newbury CC\n|Newbury CC\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |[[Wokingham (UK Parliament constituency)|Wokingham CC]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Wokingham CC\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Wokingham CC\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Wokingham CC\n|Wokingham CC\n|Wokingham CC\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |Windsor CC\n|[[East Berkshire (UK Parliament constituency)|East Berkshire CC]]\n|[[Bracknell (UK Parliament constituency)|Bracknell CC]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Windsor CC\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Windsor CC\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Windsor and Maidenhead (UK Parliament constituency)|Windsor and Maidenhead CC]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Windsor and Maidenhead CC\n|[[Maidenhead (UK Parliament constituency)|Maidenhead CC]]\n|-\n|[[Windsor (UK Parliament constituency)|New Windsor BC]]\n|Windsor CC\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n| colspan=\"3\" |''Transferred from Buckinghamshire ([[Eton and Slough (UK Parliament constituency)|Eton and Slough CC]])''\n|[[Slough (UK Parliament constituency)|Slough BC]]\n|Slough BC\n|-\n| colspan=\"7\" |BC = Borough Constituency (prior to 1950 - Parliamentary Borough or Division thereof)\nCC = County Constituency (prior to 1950 - Parliamentary County of Division thereof)\n|}\n\n==== 1918-1950 ====\nUnder the [[Representation of the People Act 1918]], the Parliamentary Borough of New Windsor and the county Division of Wokingham were abolished and replaced by the county Division of [[Windsor (UK Parliament constituency)|Windsor]], which also included [[Maidenhead]].  Eton was now included in the [[Wycombe (UK Parliament constituency)|Wycombe]] Division of Buckinghamshire The Municipal Borough of Wokingham itself was added to the Newbury Division and the Parliamentary Borough of Reading was expanded in line with the County Borough, including the absorption of [[Caversham, Reading|Caversham]], to the north of the River Thames, which had previously been part of the [[Henley (UK Parliament constituency)|Henley]] Division of Oxfordshire.\n\n==== 1950-1955 ====\nThe [[Representation of the People Act 1948]] increased the county's representation from 4 to 6 MPs.  Reading was split into the two Borough Constituencies of Reading North and Reading South and Wokingham was re-established as a County Constituency, comprising the borough of Wokingham and rural areas to the south and east of Reading, transferred from Newbury, and extending eastwards to include the Rural District of [[Easthampstead Rural District|Easthampstead]] (which incorporated [[Bracknell]]), transferred from Windsor.\n\n==== 1955-1974 ====\nUnder the [[First Periodic Review of Westminster constituencies|First Periodic Review of Westminster Constituencies]] Reading North and Reading South were recombined, with one ward of the County Borough being included in each of the Newbury and Wokingham constituencies.\n\n==== 1974-1983 ====\nUnder the Second Periodic Review, representation was increased back up to 6 MPs with the recreation of Reading North and Reading South.  The County Borough wards in Newbury and Wokingham were returned whilst Reading South (which was designated as a County Constituency) was extended southwards to include parts of the [[Wokingham Rural District|Rural District of Wokingham]], transferred from the constituency thereof.\n\n==== 1983-1997 ====\nThe Third Review reflected the changes to the county of Berkshire resulting from the [[Local Government Act 1972]] and saw major changes. The bulk of the area comprising the constituency of [[Abingdon (UK Parliament constituency)|Abingdon]] had been moved to [[Oxfordshire]], with the majority of its contents, including [[Wantage (UK Parliament constituency)|Wantage]], [[Wallingford, Oxfordshire|Wallingford]], [[Didcot]] and [[Faringdon]] being included in the new County Constituency of [[Wantage (UK Parliament constituency)|Wantage]]. The town of [[Abingdon-on-Thames]] itself, together with areas to the west of Oxford, was included in the new County Constituency of [[Oxford West and Abingdon (UK Parliament constituency)|Oxford West and Abingdon]]. The small part which was retained in Berkshire was transferred to Newbury.  The county had absorbed the Municipal Borough of Slough and the small Urban District of Eton (which together had formed the Borough Constituency of [[Eton and Slough (UK Parliament constituency)|Eton and Slough]]) from Buckinghamshire.  Slough was formed as a new Borough Constituency and Eton was added back to Windsor.\n\nA further County Constituency of [[East Berkshire (UK Parliament constituency)|East Berkshire]] was created, largely comprising the Borough of Bracknell (formerly the Rural District of Easthampstead) but also including the areas comprising the former Rural District of Windsor (including Old Windsor and Sunningdale), transferred from Windsor and Maidenhead, and the parts of the former Rural District of Eton (including Datchet) which had also been transferred from Buckinghamshire to Berkshire and were previously part of the County Constituency of [[Beaconsfield (UK Parliament constituency)|Beaconsfield]].\n\nReading North and Reading South were abolished once again and replaced by the County Constituencies of [[Reading East (UK Parliament constituency)|Reading East]] and [[Reading West (UK Parliament constituency)|Reading West]]. Reading East was formed largely from parts of Reading South, together with parts of Reading North, including Caversham.  Reading West was formed largely from parts of Reading North and extended westwards to include parts of Newbury.  North-western parts of Reading South were transferred back to Wokingham.\n\n==== 1997-2010 ====\nThe Fourth Review resulted in a further increase from 7 to 8 MPs with the abolition of Windsor and Maidenhead and the creation of the two separate County Constituencies of [[Maidenhead (UK Parliament constituency)|Maidenhead]] and [[Windsor (UK Parliament constituency)|Windsor]].  Maidenhead included Bisham and Cookham and was extended westwards to include northern parts of Wokingham.  Windsor included [[Bray, Berkshire|Bray]], Eton and the Slough ward of Foxborough. It was extended southwards to include parts of East Berkshire ([[Datchet]], [[Old Windsor]], [[Sunningdale]] and [[Ascot, Berkshire|Ascot]]).  East Berkshire was abolished with remaining parts forming the basis of the new County Constituency of Bracknell, which also included the ward of Wokingham Without, transferred from Wokingham, and [[Finchampstead]], transferred from Reading East.\n\nReading East was redesignated as a Borough Constituency, gaining parts to the east of the borough from Wokingham in exchange for areas to the south, including Shinfield.  Wokingham also added two wards from Newbury.  Finally, Reading East gained the borough ward of [[Katesgrove]] from Reading West in exchange for the ward of [[Whitley, Reading|Whitley]].\n\n==== 2010\u2013present ====\n[[Fifth Periodic Review of Westminster constituencies|Fifth Review]] - Modest changes, including the transfer of Bray from Windsor to Maidenhead, [[Binfield]] from Bracknell to Windsor and the return of Foxborough ward from Windsor to Slough.  Further marginal changes due to revision of local authority wards.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Constituency\n! Pre-2010 boundaries\n! Post-2010 boundaries\n|-\n| 1. [[Bracknell (UK Parliament constituency)|Bracknell CC]]\n| rowspan=\"8\" |[[File:BerkshireParliamentaryConstituenciesNumbered.svg]]\n| rowspan=\"8\" |[[File:BerkshireParliamentaryConstituencies2007.svg]]\n|-\n| 2. [[Maidenhead (UK Parliament constituency)|Maidenhead CC]]\n|-\n| 3. [[Newbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Newbury CC]]\n|-\n| 4. [[Reading East (UK Parliament constituency)|Reading East BC]]\n|-\n| 5. [[Reading West (UK Parliament constituency)|Reading West CC]]\n|-\n| 6. [[Slough (UK Parliament constituency)|Slough BC]]\n|-\n| 7. [[Windsor (UK Parliament constituency)|Windsor CC]]\n|-\n| 8. [[Wokingham (UK Parliament constituency)|Wokingham CC]]\n|}\n\n==Changes proposed by Boundary Commission==\nThe [[Boundary Commission for England]] submitted their final proposals in respect of the [[Sixth Periodic Review of Westminster constituencies|Sixth Periodic Review of Westminster Constituencies]] (the 2018 review) in September 2018. Although the proposals were immediately laid before [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]] they were not brought forward by the [[Government of the United Kingdom|Government]] for approval. Accordingly, they will '''not''' come into effect for the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 election]] due to take place on 12 December 2019, which will be contested using the constituency boundaries in place since 2010.\n\nUnder the terms of the [[Parliamentary Voting System and Constituencies Act 2011]], the Sixth Review was based on reducing the total number of MPs from 650 to 600 and a strict electoral parity requirement that the electorate of all constituencies should be within a range of 5% either side of the electoral quota. The review was carried out using the official UK electorate figures for 2015 and the electoral quota was set at 74,769, establishing a range of 71,031 to 78,507.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bce2018.org.uk/publications|title=Final recommendations report|last=Boundary Commission for England, 2018 Review, Associated consultation documents|date=September 2018|access-date=15 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190215215741/https://www.bce2018.org.uk/publications|archive-date=15 February 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn order to minimise the changes required, the Commission recommended combining Berkshire with Surrey as a sub-region of the South East Region. However, this involved only one ward ([[Windlesham]] in the Borough of Surrey Heath in Surrey) being transferred from the constituency of [[Surrey Heath (UK Parliament constituency)|Surrey Heath]] to the constituency of Windsor. After adjusting for this, the Commission recommended that Berkshire retained eight seats, with no name changes, of which four (Bracknell, Maidenhead, Slough and Wokingham) were unchanged. Elsewhere, Reading West would gain a further two [[West Berkshire|District of West Berkshire]] wards ([[Basildon, Berkshire|Basildon]] and [[Bucklebury]]) from Newbury and the [[Reading, Berkshire|Borough of Reading]] ward of [[Battle (Reading ward)|Battle]] would be transferred from Reading West to Reading East.<ref name=\":0\" />\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|'''Current constituencies'''\n|'''Electorate'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bce2018.org.uk/publications|title=The electorate of each region subdivided by both local authorities and each existing constituency|last=Boundary Commission for England, 2018 Review, Associated consultation documents (Document type: Electoral data)|date=24 February 2016|access-date=15 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190215215741/https://www.bce2018.org.uk/publications|archive-date=15 February 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|'''Proposed constituencies'''<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bce2018.org.uk/publications|title=Final recommendations constituency list (with wards)|last=Boundary Commission for England, 2018 Review, Associated consultation documents|date=September 2018|access-date=15 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190215215741/https://www.bce2018.org.uk/publications|archive-date=15 February 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|'''Electorate'''<ref name=\":1\" />\n|-\n|[[Bracknell (UK Parliament constituency)|Bracknell]] CC\n|76,917\n|Bracknell BC\n|76,917\n|-\n|[[Maidenhead (UK Parliament constituency)|Maidenhead]] CC\n|71,834\n|Maidenhead CC\n|71,834\n|-\n|[[Newbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Newbury]] CC\n|78,963\n|Newbury CC\n|71,737\n|-\n|[[Reading East (UK Parliament constituency)|Reading East]] BC\n|67,846\n|Reading East BC\n|73,626\n|-\n|[[Reading West (UK Parliament constituency)|Reading West]] CC\n|69,709\n|Reading West CC\n|71,155\n|-\n|[[Slough (UK Parliament constituency)|Slough]] BC\n|76,668\n|Slough BC\n|76,668\n|-\n|[[Windsor (UK Parliament constituency)|Windsor]] CC\n|68,834\n|Windsor CC\n|68,834<sup>1</sup>\n|-\n|[[Wokingham (UK Parliament constituency)|Wokingham]] CC\n|76,905\n|Wokingham CC\n|76,905\n|-\n|\n|'''587,676'''\n|\n|'''587,676'''\n|}\n<sup>1</sup>Also includes part in Surrey (3,256)\n\n==Results maps==\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"80\">\nFile:BerkshireParliamentaryConstituency1992Results.svg|'''1983'''\nFile:BerkshireParliamentaryConstituency1992Results.svg|'''1987'''\nFile:BerkshireParliamentaryConstituency1992Results.svg|'''1992'''\nFile:BerkshireParliamentaryConstituency2001Results.svg|'''1997'''\nFile:BerkshireParliamentaryConstituency2001Results.svg|'''2001'''