es Townshend Murdoch|Murdoch]]\n| colspan=\"3\" bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|[[George William Palmer (England)|Palmer]]\n| colspan=\"4\" bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|[[Rufus Isaacs, 1st Marquess of Reading|Isaacs]]\n| bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" colspan=\"5\" |[[Leslie Orme Wilson|Wilson]]\n| bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |[[Edward Cecil George Cadogan|Cadogan]]\n| bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |[[Somerville Hastings|Hastings]]\n| bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |[[Sir Herbert Williams, 1st Baronet|Williams]]\n| bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |[[Somerville Hastings|Hastings]]\n| bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" colspan=\"3\" |[[Alfred Bakewell Howitt|Howitt]]\n| bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |[[Ian Mikardo|Mikardo]]\n|-\n|[[Windsor (UK Parliament constituency)|Windsor]]\n| bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" colspan=\"2\" |[[Robert Richardson-Gardner|Richardson-Gardner]]\n| bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" colspan=\"7\" |[[Sir Francis Barry, 1st Baronet|Barry]]\n| bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" colspan=\"5\" |Mason\n| bgcolor=\"{{Coalition Conservative/meta/color}}\" colspan=\"3\" |[[Ernest Gardner|Gardner]]\n| bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" colspan=\"6\" |[[Annesley Ashworth Somerville|Somerville]]\n| bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" colspan=\"2\" |[[Charles Edward Mott-Radclyffe|Mott-Radclyffe]]\n|-\n|[[Wokingham (UK Parliament constituency)|Wokingham]] \n| bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" colspan=\"5\" |[[Sir George Russell, 4th Baronet|Russell]]\n| bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" colspan=\"2\" |[[Oliver Young|Young]]\n| bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" colspan=\"7\" |[[Ernest Gardner|Gardner]]\n| colspan=\"11\" |\n|}\n\n===1950 to 1983===\n{{legend2|{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}|[[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]|border=1px solid #aaaaaa}}\n{{legend2|{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}|[[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]|border=1px solid #aaaaaa}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Constituency\n!1950\n!1951\n!''53''\n!1955\n!1959\n!1964\n!1966\n!1970\n!Feb 74\n!Oct 74\n!1979\n|-\n|[[Abingdon (UK Parliament constituency)|Abingdon]]\n| bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" colspan=\"2\" |[[Ralph Glyn, 1st Baron Glyn|Glyn]]\n| bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" colspan=\"8\" |[[Airey Neave|Neave]]\n| bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |[[Thomas Yates Benyon|T. Benyon]]\n|-\n|[[Newbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Newbury]]\n| bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" colspan=\"5\" |[[Anthony Hurd|Hurd]]\n| bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" colspan=\"3\" |[[John Astor|Astor]]\n| colspan=\"3\" bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |[[Michael McNair-Wilson|McNair-Wilson]]\n|-\n|[[Reading North (UK Parliament constituency)|Reading North]]\n| bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |[[Kim Mackay|K. Mackay]]\n| bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" colspan=\"2\" |[[Frederic Bennett|Bennett]]\n| colspan=\"5\" |\n| colspan=\"3\" bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |[[Tony Durant|Durant]]\n|-\n|[[Reading South (UK Parliament constituency)|Reading South]] (1950\u201355, 74-83) / [[Reading (UK Parliament constituency)|Reading]] (1955\u201374)\n| bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" colspan=\"4\" |[[Ian Mikardo|Mikardo]]\n| bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" colspan=\"2\" |[[Peter Emery|Emery]]\n| bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |[[John Michael Hubert Lee|Lee]]\n| colspan=\"4\" bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |[[Gerard Vaughan (British politician)|Vaughan]]\n|-\n|[[Windsor (UK Parliament constituency)|Windsor]] / [[Windsor and Maidenhead (UK Parliament constituency)|Windsor and Maidenhead]] (1974)\n| bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" colspan=\"7\" |[[Charles Edward Mott-Radclyffe|Mott-Radclyffe]]\n| colspan=\"4\" bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |[[Alan Glyn|Glyn]]\n|-\n|[[Wokingham (UK Parliament constituency)|Wokingham]]\n| bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" colspan=\"4\" |[[Peter Remnant|Remnant]]\n| colspan=\"7\" bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |[[William van Straubenzee|van Straubenzee]]\n|}\n\n===1983 to present===\n\n{{legend2|{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}|[[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]|border=1px solid #aaaaaa}} \n{{legend2|{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}|[[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]|border=1px solid #aaaaaa}}\n{{legend2|{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}|[[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]]|border=1px solid #aaaaaa}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Constituency\n!1983\n!1987\n!1992\n!''93''\n!1997\n!2001\n!2005\n!2010\n!2015\n!2017\n!''19''\n!2019\n|-\n|[[Newbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Newbury]]\n| colspan=\"2\" bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|[[Michael McNair-Wilson|McNair-Wilson]]\n| bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |[[Judith Chaplin|Chaplin]]\n| colspan=\"3\" bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\" |[[David Rendel|Rendel]]\n| colspan=\"5\" bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |[[Richard Benyon|R. Benyon]]\n| bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|[[Laura Farris|Farris]]\n|-\n|[[Reading West (UK Parliament constituency)|Reading West]]\n| colspan=\"4\" bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|[[Tony Durant|Durant]]\n| colspan=\"3\" bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |[[Martin Salter|Salter]]\n| colspan=\"5\" bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |[[Alok Sharma|Sharma]]\n|-\n|[[Reading East (UK Parliament constituency)|Reading East]]\n| colspan=\"4\" bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|[[Gerard Vaughan (British politician)|Vaughan]]\n| colspan=\"2\" bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |[[Jane Griffiths (politician)|Griffiths]]\n| colspan=\"3\" bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |[[Rob Wilson|Wilson]]\n| colspan=\"3\" bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |[[Matt Rodda|Rodda]]\n|-\n|[[Windsor and Maidenhead (UK Parliament constituency)|Windsor and Maidenhead]] / [[Windsor (UK Parliament constituency)|Windsor]] (1997)\n| colspan=\"2\" bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|[[Alan Glyn|Glyn]]\n| colspan=\"4\" bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |[[Michael Trend|Trend]]\n| colspan=\"6\" bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |[[Adam Afriyie|Afriyie]]\n|-\n|[[Wokingham (UK Parliament constituency)|Wokingham]]\n| bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|[[William van Straubenzee|van Straubenzee]]\n| colspan=\"11\" bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |[[John Redwood|Redwood]]\n|-\n|[[Slough (UK Parliament constituency)|Slough]]\n| colspan=\"4\" bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |[[John Arthur Watts|Watts]]\n| colspan=\"5\" bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |[[Fiona Mactaggart|Mactaggart]]\n| colspan=\"3\" bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |[[Tanmanjeet Singh Dhesi|Dhesi]]\n|-\n|[[East Berkshire (UK Parliament constituency)|East Berkshire]] / [[Bracknell (UK Parliament constituency)|Bracknell]] (1997)\n| colspan=\"7\" bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |[[Andrew James MacKay|A. MacKay]]\n| colspan=\"3\" bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |[[Phillip Lee (British politician)|Lee]]\n| bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\" |[[Phillip Lee (British politician)|\u2192]]\n| bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|[[James Sunderland (politician)|Sunderland]]\n|-\n|[[Maidenhead (UK Parliament constituency)|Maidenhead]]\n| colspan=\"4\" |\n| colspan=\"8\" bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |[[Theresa May|May]]\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Parliamentary constituencies in the South East (region)]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=\"nb\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin}}\n;General\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.official-documents.gov.uk/document/cm70/7032/7032.pdf |title=Boundary Commission for England: Fifth Periodical Report |publisher=Crown Copyright |work=[[Boundary Commission for England]] |accessdate=6 November 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726095050/http://www.official-documents.gov.uk/document/cm70/7032/7032.pdf |archivedate=26 July 2011 }}\n*{{cite book|title=[[Boundaries of Parliamentary Constituencies 1885\u20131972]]|last=Craig|first=Frederick Walter Scott|authorlink=F. W. S. Craig|coauthors= |year=1972 |publisher=Political Reference Publications |location=[[Chichester]], Sussex |isbn=0-900178-13-2}}\n\n;Specific\n{{refend}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{UK constituencies}}\n{{Berkshire}}\n\n[[Category:Government and politics of Slough]]\n[[Category:Lists of United Kingdom Parliamentary constituencies in England|Berkshire]]\n[[Category:Politics of Berkshire]]\n[[Category:Parliamentary constituencies in Berkshire| ]]\n[[Category:Parliamentary constituencies in South East England| ]]\n[[Category:Berkshire-related lists|Parliamentary]]\n", "name_user": "Doktorbuk", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eChanges proposed by Boundary Commission", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Parliamentary_constituencies_in_Berkshire"}
{"title_page": "West Loch disaster", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict= West Loch disaster\n|image=USS LST-480 3.jpg\n|image_size=300px\n|caption= {{USS|LST-39||2}} and {{USS|LST-480||2}} still ablaze on 22 May 1944.\n|date=21 May 1944\n|place=West Loch, [[Naval Station Pearl Harbor|Pearl Harbor U.S. Naval Base]], Hawaii\n|casus=\n|result=163 killed<br/>396 injured\n}}\nThe '''West Loch Disaster''' was a maritime accident during [[World War II]] at [[Naval Station Pearl Harbor|Pearl Harbor U.S. Naval Base]] in Hawaii. The incident, which occurred just after 3:00 p.m. on Sunday, May 21, 1944, began following an explosion in a staging area for [[Landing Ship, Tank|Landing Ships, Tank (LSTs)]]<!-- This is the proper plural form... --> and other [[amphibious assault ship]]s in West Loch. A fire quickly spread among the ships being prepared for [[Operation Forager]], the invasion of the Japanese-held [[Mariana Islands]]. Over the next 24 hours, six LSTs sank, 163 [[United States Navy|naval personnel]] died, and 396 were injured.\n\nA subsequent [[Naval Board of Inquiry]] never determined the exact cause of the disaster but concluded that the initial explosion was caused when a [[Mortar (weapon)|mortar round]] aboard {{USS|LST-353||2}} detonated during an unloading operation because it was either dropped or went off when gasoline vapors ignited. The incident \u2013 together with the [[Port Chicago disaster]] two months later \u2013 led to major changes in weapons-handling practices within the United States Navy.\n\nThe LST wreckage was quickly cleared in a salvage operation and dumped at sea {{convert|3|mi|nmi km|lk=on|abbr=on}} south of Hawaii.<!--the island, or should this say Oahu?--> Only the hull of the partially beached {{USS|LST-480||2}} was left in West Loch. A press blackout was enforced and naval personnel were ordered not to talk about the incident. The disaster was classified until 1960 and is therefore not well known.\n\nThe disaster has been the focus of considerable speculation that during the salvage and removal of the wrecks from West Loch, the U.S. Navy might have found the remains of a Japanese [[midget submarine]], possibly the fifth Japanese midget submarine used in the [[Attack on Pearl Harbor|attack in December 1941]].\n\n==Background==\n[[File:PearlHarbor Sm.jpg|thumb|right|[[Pearl Harbor]] naval base. The West Loch is the arm of Pearl Harbor on the left side of the image.]]\nIn May 1944, the West Loch area of [[Pearl Harbor]] was unusually crowded with various vessels as it was being used as a staging area for the upcoming [[Operation Forager]]. Twenty-nine [[Landing Ship, Tank|Landing Ships, Tank]]<!-- This is the proper plural form... --> (LSTs) were tied up, beam to beam, at six Tare piers.<ref name=Oliver2005/><ref name=USNationalParksService27Apr2001/> Many of the LSTs, in addition to carrying their own complement of munitions and fuel, were also fully loaded with the munitions, fuel, vehicles, equipment, and other general stores required by the [[2nd Marine Division (United States)|2nd]] and [[4th Marine Division (United States)|4th Marine Division]]s for the invasion of the Marianas, that was to begin in mid-June. To aid quick deployment once ashore, [[Octane rating|high-octane gasoline]] was stored in barrels on deck.<ref name=Oliver2005/>\n\nIn the weeks leading up to the incident, the vessels and crews had all been training for the upcoming invasion. The LSTs were each crewed by around 120 Navy sailors or Coast Guardsmen, and manned by around 200 Marine loaders, drivers and mechanics.<ref name=Oliver2005/><ref name= USNationalParksService27Apr2001/> The rapid expansion of the fleet meant many of the crews were made up of inexperienced sailors and [[United States Marine Corps|Marines]]. On 21 May, many of the LSTs had only half their crew aboard because, after a week of intensive training, most officers and ratings had been given shore leave.<ref name=Oliver2005/>\n\n==Explosion==\n[[File:LST-39 (ship).jpg|thumb|right| The burned hulk of '''LST-39''' on 21 May 1944.]]\n[[File:LST-480 following West Loch disaster.jpg|thumb|right|{{USS|LST-480||2}} on 22 May 1944.]]\n[[File:USS LST-480 fire2.jpg|thumb|right|''LST-480'' burns again on 23 May 1944. The sunken {{USS|LST-353||2}} where the disaster originated lies off her starboard bow]]\nAt 15:08, {{USS|LST-353||2}}, moored at Tare 8, exploded, sending a large fireball into the sky.<ref name=Oliver2005/><ref name= USNationalParksService27Apr2001/> The noise was heard miles away at Pearl Harbor Headquarters. More explosions of increasing intensity followed, sparking fears of a Japanese attack or even an earthquake. Fire and debris raining down on the fuel and munitions stored on the decks of other LSTs had caused an explosive chain reaction.<ref name=Oliver2005/><ref name= AP19May2009/> Within minutes, 200 men had been blown into the water. Eleven wooden buildings on the shore were destroyed and vehicles blown on their side.<ref name=Oliver2005/> In all, 20 buildings were damaged.<ref name=USNationalParksService27Apr2001/>\n\nInitial efforts by the crews to fight the fires were impeded by the heat, although some ships further away managed to muster damage control parties. Many of the LSTs tied together at Tare 8 began to sink. Within the hour, [[Admiral (United States)|Admiral]] [[Richmond K. Turner]] was directing fire-fighting efforts from a launch.<ref name=Oliver2005/>\n\nVarious LSTs managed to move to safety under their own power or with assistance by [[tugboat]]s. However others were abandoned and allowed to drift, spreading fires, before sinking in the channel. Leaking oil ignited on the water also spread fires to Tares 7 and 9 even though they had been unharmed after the first explosions at Tare 8.<ref name=Oliver2005/> Eventually tugboats and foam-carrying salvage ships from Pearl Harbor arrived to fight the spreading fires. One ship managed to turn a drifting LST away from a collision course with an ammunition ship docked across the loch at the ammunition depot.<ref name= AP19May2009/>\n\nA final explosion occurred at 22:30;<ref name=Oliver2005/> while several LSTs continued to burn for 24 hours.<ref name= USNationalParksService27Apr2001/> In total, the harbor tugs {{USS|Osceola|YTB-129|2}}, {{ship||Hoga|YT-146|2}}, and {{USS|Geronimo|YTM-119|2}}, the net tender {{USS|Tamaha|YNT-12|2}}, the chartered tug ''Mikioi'', and smaller tugs ''YTL-233'', ''YTL-306'', ''YTL-307'', ''YTL-308'', ''YTL-309'', and ''YTL-339'' were damaged while engaged in fire control efforts.<ref name=\"cressman\"/>\n\n==Casualties==\nThe initial official account listed 27 dead and 100 missing.<ref name=DallasMorningNews21May1997/> The majority of sources state the final death toll as 163 men, with a further 396 wounded.<ref name=USNationalParksService27Apr2001/><ref name=AP19May2009/><ref name=AP22May2009/> However, in 2005 the magazine, ''Sea Classics'', claimed the total dead was 392, of which 163 were sailors. The other 229 were Marines from the newly formed [[2nd Marine Division (United States)|2nd]] and [[4th Marine Division (United States)|4th Marine Division]]s, while Army dead were not recorded in the confusion.<ref name=Oliver2005/> Pearl Harbor attack survivor and historical researcher, Ray Emory, also disputes the official death toll; he believes 132 men died at West Loch.<ref name=AP22May2009/>\n\n==Investigation==\nA [[Naval Board of Inquiry]], under [[Rear Admiral (United States)|Rear Admiral]] [[John F. Shafroth Jr.]], was opened in Pearl Harbor the following day.<ref name=Oliver2005/> An early theory that the incident was the result of a [[Imperial Japanese Navy|Japanese submarine attack]] was dismissed as impractical because of the depth of the West Loch and the presence of anti-submarine nets.<ref name=Oliver2005/>\n\nThe [[Executive officer#United States|executive officer]] of ''LST-353'' stated that immediately prior to the explosion, [[United States Army|Army]] [[stevedore]]s were unloading mortar ammunition from a [[Landing craft tank|Landing craft tank (LCT)]] on the deck of his ship. The procedure to remove the {{convert|4.2|in|mm|abbr=on}} mortar rounds was being undertaken because training had proved [[M2 4.2 inch mortar|M2 mortar]]s could not be fired accurately from LCTs.<ref name=Oliver2005/><ref name=AP19May2009/> The enquiry was told the unit given the order to unload the mortar rounds had received no training for the task.<ref name=AP22May2009/> Meanwhile, 80 drums of fuel were stacked just {{convert|15|ft|m|abbr=on}} from the elevator being used to unload the LCT.<ref name=Oliver2005/>\n\nFollowing testimony, the Naval Enquiry Board concluded that a mortar round exploded on ''LST-353'' sparking a chain reaction. However it could not determine the actual cause of the detonation because all those nearest to the explosion were killed.<ref name=AP19May2009/> This conclusion was sustained by subsequent reviews. The two most plausible explanations were considered to be:\n#the accidental dropping of a mortar round being unloaded from the LCT on the ''LST-353''\n#the ignition of gasoline vapors from high-octane fuel drums stored on the deck of ''LST-353''.<ref name=Oliver2005/><ref name=USNationalParksService27Apr2001/> The source being a cigarette (although banned) or [[welding]], which had also been occurring that day aboard ''LST-353''.<ref name=AP19May2009/>\n\nThe enquiry also heard the conduct of the inexperienced crews may have exacerbated the disaster. [[Lieutenant commander (United States)|Lieutenant Commander]] Joseph B. Hoyt, [[USNR]], the Commander of LST Group 39, Flotilla 13, criticized many of the LST crews for abandoning their vessels too early, leaving them to sink or drift, rather than fire-fighting or attempting to beach them. However he praised the efforts of the crew from ''LST-274'', which received heavy damage but was saved.\nSeveral crews and skippers were called to account for inadequate reactions to the emergency, although the severity of the conditions were cited as mitigating factors.<ref name=Oliver2005/>\n\nIn the end no [[Court-martial|courts-martial]] or [[Letter of reprimand|letters of reprimand]] were issued to anyone involved. The practice of loading fuel and munitions aboard closely moored vessels was deemed to be necessary under the conditions of war and the layout of Pearl Harbor U.S. Navy Base. A recommendation by the Board to avoid nesting in future was criticized by Admiral [[Chester W. Nimitz]] as impractical.<ref name=Oliver2005/><ref name=USNationalParksService27Apr2001/>\n\n==Reporting==\nThe [[United States military]] ordered a [[press blackout]] following the incident. The official inquiry was marked Top Secret and survivors and eyewitnesses were not permitted to mention the incident in letters home.<ref name=Oliver2005/><ref name=DallasMorningNews21May1997/> Four days after the incident, the authorities released a one-paragraph statement noting an explosion had caused \"some loss of life, a number of injuries and resulted in the destruction of several small vessels\". It was only after Operation Forager that a fuller account was released to the press.<ref name=DallasMorningNews21May1997/> The entire incident was not declassified and made public until 1960.<ref name=Oliver2005/>\n\nAs a result of the secrecy surrounding the incident, it has been asserted that the public knows little about Pearl Harbor's \"second disaster\".<ref name=DallasMorningNews21May1997/><ref name= AP22May2009/> As of 1997, the only book about the incident, ''The West Loch Story'', was privately published by survivor, William L.C. Johnson. He alleges that a full account had not emerged from the Navy until 1964, and that the incident had been caused by careless smoking.<ref name=DallasMorningNews21May1997/>\n\n==Impact on Operation Forager==\nSix LSTs were sunk<ref name=Oliver2005/><ref name=USNationalParksService27Apr2001/> (''LST-39'', ''LST-43'', ''LST-69'', ''LST-179'', ''LST-353'', and ''LST-480''),<ref name=\"cressman\"/> two already carrying smaller, fully loaded [[Landing craft tank]]s (''LCT-961'', 963 and 983)<ref name=\"cressman\"/> lashed to their decks.<ref name=Oliver2005/> Several LSTs were damaged and/or ran aground. Four (including LST-205 and LST-225)<ref name=\"cressman\"/> could not be repaired in time for the invasion.<ref name=Oliver2005/> Seventeen tracked landing vehicles (LVT) and eight {{convert|155|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} guns were destroyed.<ref name=\"cressman\"/> Other sources place the total number of destroyed LSTs at nine.<ref name=AP19May2009/> With reinforcement of the fleet from elsewhere, and through quick repair efforts, Operation Forager was only delayed by one day as a result of the incident, with the operation commencing essentially as planned three weeks later.<ref name=Oliver2005/>\n\n==Medal of Honor==\nBoatswain's Mate 2nd Class [[Francis P. Hammerberg]], a Navy diver, posthumously received the [[Medal of Honor]] for heroism on February 17, 1945, during salvage operations on an LST sunk in the West Loch incident.  He was killed in a cave-in while attempting to tunnel under one of the sunken LSTs.  He was the only service member in World War II, and the last person of all, to receive the Medal of Honor for a non-combat action.  (Prior to World War II, the Navy had frequently awarded the Medal of Honor for non-combat heroism.)\n\n==Memorials==\n[[File:US Navy 030521-N-8157C-040 59 years after explosions rang out in Pearl Harbor^rsquo,s West Loch, a memorial of disaster reminds all of a quiet Sunday afternoon on May 21, 1944.jpg|thumb|right|The rusting remains of {{USS|LST-480||2}} at  {{coord|21|21|26.04|N|157|59|50.05|W|scale:10000|display=inline}}.]]\n\nIn the weeks following the disaster, all wreckage was salvaged and removed, with the exception of {{USS|LST-480||2}} (sometimes reported as ''LST-353''<ref name=AP19May2009/>). Its rusting bow was left where it was beached during the disaster.<ref name=Oliver2005/><ref name=USNationalParksService27Apr2001/><ref name= AP22May2009/> In April 1995, the first memorial to the disaster was unveiled: a table-sized plaque sited on the shore of the loch.<ref name=DallasMorningNews21May1997/> At the behest of [[United States Congress|Congress]], gravestones of unidentified victims in the [[National Memorial Cemetery of the Pacific]] were amended in the 2000s (decade) from recording simply \"unknown\", to \"Unknown, West Loch Disaster, May 21, 1944\".<ref name=AP19May2009/> The Navy commemorated the 65th anniversary of the disaster on 21 May 2009.<ref name=AP19May2009/>\n\n==Legacy==\nAs a result of the incident, and the [[Port Chicago disaster]] two months later, the Navy drastically changed its ordnance-handling procedures. It insisted on full training for handlers, munitions to be redesigned for safer handling, and that vessels should no longer be nested together when ammunition was being loaded or handled.<ref name=AP22May2009/>\n\nIt is also possible that the salvage operation undertaken to clear the loch after the disaster inadvertently lengthened the hunt for the \"fifth midget submarine\" involved in the 1941 attack on Pearl Harbor. After three pieces of a midget submarine were discovered three miles south of Pearl Harbor, a working theory was developed that this was the only submarine in a group of five Japanese [[Ko-hyoteki class submarine]]s involved in the attack that had not yet been accounted for. Researchers posited that it had penetrated the harbor to attack [[Battleship Row]], before escaping into West Loch and being scuttled by the two-man crew. Lying on the bed of the loch, it was then salvaged along with the remains of the LSTs, LCTs and landing tanks, and then dumped at sea.<ref name=LATimes7Dec2009/><ref name=NovaTranscript/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of accidents and disasters by death toll#Explosions|List of accidents and disasters by death toll, explosions]]\n*[[List of accidents and incidents involving transport or storage of ammunition]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"cressman\">{{cite book|title=The Official Chronology of the U.S. Navy in World War II|author=Cressman, Robert J.|publisher=Naval Institute Press|year=2000|isbn=1-55750-149-1|page=[https://archive.org/details/TheOfficialChronologyOfTheUSNavyInWorldWarII/page/229 229]|url=https://archive.org/details/TheOfficialChronologyOfTheUSNavyInWorldWarII/page/229}}</ref><ref name=NovaTranscript>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/nova/transcripts/3701_killersubs.html \n |title=Killer Subs in Pearl Harbour \n |publisher=PBS \n |work=Transcript, Nova \n |date=5 January 2010 \n |accessdate=12 April 2010 \n |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5owWRjeJv?url=http://www.pbs.org/wgbh/nova/transcripts/3701_killersubs.html \n |archivedate=12 April 2010 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref><ref name=LATimes7Dec2009>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/nation-and-world/la-sci-minisub7-2009dec07,0,6991792.story |title=Pearl Harbor mini-submarine mystery solved? |publisher=LA Times |date=7 December 2009 |accessdate=12 April 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5owWR6r8n?url=http://www.latimes.com/news/nation-and-world/la-sci-minisub7-2009dec07%2C0%2C6991792.story |archivedate=12 April 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=Oliver2005>{{cite web|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qa4442/is_200511/ai_n16059243/|title=Navy's hushed up tragedy at West Loch|publisher=Challenge Publications|work=Sea Classics magazine|author=Oliver, A Alan|date=November 2005|accessdate=12 April 2010}}</ref><ref name=USNationalParksService27Apr2001>{{cite web|url=http://www.nps.gov/archive/usar/scrs/scrs2z.htm |title=West Loch disaster |work=Submerged Cultural Resources Study:USS Arizona and Pearl Harbor National Historic Landmark, Chapter II: Historical Record |publisher=US National Park Service |date=27 April 2001 |accessdate=12 April 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5owIMj68d?url=http://www.nps.gov/archive/usar/scrs/scrs2z.htm |archivedate=12 April 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=AP19May2009>{{cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/wirestory?id=7621375&page=1 |title=Navy Recalls Bravery at WWII's West Loch Disaster |publisher=ABC News / Associated Press |date=19 May 2009 |accessdate=12 April 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5owIsa8VQ?url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/wirestory?id=7621375 |archivedate=12 April 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=AP22May2009>{{cite news|url=http://www.armytimes.com/news/2009/05/ap_west_loch_disaster_052109/ |title=Deadly 1944 Pearl Harbor disaster remembered |publisher=Army Times / Associated Press |date=2 May 2009 |accessdate=12 April 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5owRwkfl9?url=http://www.armytimes.com/news/2009/05/ap_west_loch_disaster_052109/ |archivedate=12 April 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=DallasMorningNews21May1997>{{cite news|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19970521&slug=2540393 |title=Second Tragedy at Pearl Harbor Is Little-Known |publisher=Dallas Morning News |date=21 May 1997 |accessdate=12 April 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5owLF9bbi?url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19970521 |archivedate=12 April 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>}}\n\n[[Category:Explosions in 1944]]\n[[Category:Industrial fires and explosions in the United States]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in May 1944]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in the United States]]\n[[Category:United States Navy in the 20th century]]\n[[Category:History of Oahu]]\n[[Category:Ship fires]]\n[[Category:Non-combat internal explosions on warships]]\n[[Category:1944 in Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Transportation disasters in Hawaii]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict= West Loch disaster\n|image=USS LST-480 3.jpg\n|image_size=300px\n|caption= {{USS|LST-39||2}} and {{USS|LST-480||2}} still ablaze on 22 May 1944.\n|date=21 May 1944\n|place=West Loch, [[Naval Station Pearl Harbor|Pearl Harbor U.S. Naval Base]], Hawaii\n|casus=\n|result=163 killed<br/>396 injured\n}}\nThe '''West Loch Disaster''' was a maritime accident during [[World War II]] at [[Naval Station Pearl Harbor|Pearl Harbor U.S. Naval Base]] in Hawaii. The incident, which occurred just after 3:00 p.m. on Sunday, May 21, 1944, began following an explosion in a staging area for [[Landing Ship, Tank|Landing Ships, Tank (LSTs)]]<!-- This is the proper plural form... --> and other [[amphibious assault ship]]s in West Loch. A fire quickly spread among the ships being prepared for [[Operation Forager]], the invasion of the Japanese-held [[Mariana Islands]]. Over the next 24 hours, six LSTs sank, 163 [[United States Navy|naval personnel]] died, and 396 were injured.\n\nA subsequent [[Naval Board of Inquiry]] never determined the exact cause of the disaster but concluded that the initial explosion was caused when a [[Mortar (weapon)|mortar round]] aboard {{USS|LST-353||2}} detonated during an unloading operation because it was either dropped or went off when gasoline vapors ignited. The incident \u2013 together with the [[Port Chicago disaster]] two months later \u2013 led to major changes in weapons-handling practices within the United States Navy.\n\nThe LST wreckage was quickly cleared in a salvage operation and dumped at sea {{convert|3|mi|nmi km|lk=on|abbr=on}} south of Hawaii.<!--the island, or should this say Oahu?--> Only the hull of the partially beached {{USS|LST-480||2}} was left in West Loch. A press blackout was enforced and naval personnel were ordered not to talk about the incident. The disaster was classified until 1960 and is therefore not well known.\n\nThe disaster has been the focus of considerable speculation that during the salvage and removal of the wrecks from West Loch, the U.S. Navy found might have found the remains of a Japanese [[midget submarine]], possibly the fifth Japanese midget submarine used in the [[Attack on Pearl Harbor|attack in December 1941]].\n\n==Background==\n[[File:PearlHarbor Sm.jpg|thumb|right|[[Pearl Harbor]] naval base. The West Loch is the arm of Pearl Harbor on the left side of the image.]]\nIn May 1944, the West Loch area of [[Pearl Harbor]] was unusually crowded with various vessels as it was being used as a staging area for the upcoming [[Operation Forager]]. Twenty-nine [[Landing Ship, Tank|Landing Ships, Tank]]<!-- This is the proper plural form... --> (LSTs) were tied up, beam to beam, at six Tare piers.<ref name=Oliver2005/><ref name=USNationalParksService27Apr2001/> Many of the LSTs, in addition to carrying their own complement of munitions and fuel, were also fully loaded with the munitions, fuel, vehicles, equipment, and other general stores required by the [[2nd Marine Division (United States)|2nd]] and [[4th Marine Division (United States)|4th Marine Division]]s for the invasion of the Marianas, that was to begin in mid-June. To aid quick deployment once ashore, [[Octane rating|high-octane gasoline]] was stored in barrels on deck.<ref name=Oliver2005/>\n\nIn the weeks leading up to the incident, the vessels and crews had all been training for the upcoming invasion. The LSTs were each crewed by around 120 Navy sailors or Coast Guardsmen, and manned by around 200 Marine loaders, drivers and mechanics.<ref name=Oliver2005/><ref name= USNationalParksService27Apr2001/> The rapid expansion of the fleet meant many of the crews were made up of inexperienced sailors and [[United States Marine Corps|Marines]]. On 21 May, many of the LSTs had only half their crew aboard because, after a week of intensive training, most officers and ratings had been given shore leave.<ref name=Oliver2005/>\n\n==Explosion==\n[[File:LST-39 (ship).jpg|thumb|right| The burned hulk of '''LST-39''' on 21 May 1944.]]\n[[File:LST-480 following West Loch disaster.jpg|thumb|right|{{USS|LST-480||2}} on 22 May 1944.]]\n[[File:USS LST-480 fire2.jpg|thumb|right|''LST-480'' burns again on 23 May 1944. The sunken {{USS|LST-353||2}} where the disaster originated lies off her starboard bow]]\nAt 15:08, {{USS|LST-353||2}}, moored at Tare 8, exploded, sending a large fireball into the sky.<ref name=Oliver2005/><ref name= USNationalParksService27Apr2001/> The noise was heard miles away at Pearl Harbor Headquarters. More explosions of increasing intensity followed, sparking fears of a Japanese attack or even an earthquake. Fire and debris raining down on the fuel and munitions stored on the decks of other LSTs had caused an explosive chain reaction.<ref name=Oliver2005/><ref name= AP19May2009/> Within minutes, 200 men had been blown into the water. Eleven wooden buildings on the shore were destroyed and vehicles blown on their side.<ref name=Oliver2005/> In all, 20 buildings were damaged.<ref name=USNationalParksService27Apr2001/>\n\nInitial efforts by the crews to fight the fires were impeded by the heat, although some ships further away managed to muster damage control parties. Many of the LSTs tied together at Tare 8 began to sink. Within the hour, [[Admiral (United States)|Admiral]] [[Richmond K. Turner]] was directing fire-fighting efforts from a launch.<ref name=Oliver2005/>\n\nVarious LSTs managed to move to safety under their own power or with assistance by [[tugboat]]s. However others were abandoned and allowed to drift, spreading fires, before sinking in the channel. Leaking oil ignited on the water also spread fires to Tares 7 and 9 even though they had been unharmed after the first explosions at Tare 8.<ref name=Oliver2005/> Eventually tugboats and foam-carrying salvage ships from Pearl Harbor arrived to fight the spreading fires. One ship managed to turn a drifting LST away from a collision course with an ammunition ship docked across the loch at the ammunition depot.<ref name= AP19May2009/>\n\nA final explosion occurred at 22:30;<ref name=Oliver2005/> while several LSTs continued to burn for 24 hours.<ref name= USNationalParksService27Apr2001/> In total, the harbor tugs {{USS|Osceola|YTB-129|2}}, {{ship||Hoga|YT-146|2}}, and {{USS|Geronimo|YTM-119|2}}, the net tender {{USS|Tamaha|YNT-12|2}}, the chartered tug ''Mikioi'', and smaller tugs ''YTL-233'', ''YTL-306'', ''YTL-307'', ''YTL-308'', ''YTL-309'', and ''YTL-339'' were damaged while engaged in fire control efforts.<ref name=\"cressman\"/>\n\n==Casualties==\nThe initial official account listed 27 dead and 100 missing.<ref name=DallasMorningNews21May1997/> The majority of sources state the final death toll as 163 men, with a further 396 wounded.<ref name=USNationalParksService27Apr2001/><ref name=AP19May2009/><ref name=AP22May2009/> However, in 2005 the magazine, ''Sea Classics'', claimed the total dead was 392, of which 163 were sailors. The other 229 were Marines from the newly formed [[2nd Marine Division (United States)|2nd]] and [[4th Marine Division (United States)|4th Marine Division]]s, while Army dead were not recorded in the confusion.<ref name=Oliver2005/> Pearl Harbor attack survivor and historical researcher, Ray Emory, also disputes the official death toll; he believes 132 men died at West Loch.<ref name=AP22May2009/>\n\n==Investigation==\nA [[Naval Board of Inquiry]], under [[Rear Admiral (United States)|Rear Admiral]] [[John F. Shafroth Jr.]], was opened in Pearl Harbor the following day.<ref name=Oliver2005/> An early theory that the incident was the result of a [[Imperial Japanese Navy|Japanese submarine attack]] was dismissed as impractical because of the depth of the West Loch and the presence of anti-submarine nets.<ref name=Oliver2005/>\n\nThe [[Executive officer#United States|executive officer]] of ''LST-353'' stated that immediately prior to the explosion, [[United States Army|Army]] [[stevedore]]s were unloading mortar ammunition from a [[Landing craft tank|Landing craft tank (LCT)]] on the deck of his ship. The procedure to remove the {{convert|4.2|in|mm|abbr=on}} mortar rounds was being undertaken because training had proved [[M2 4.2 inch mortar|M2 mortar]]s could not be fired accurately from LCTs.<ref name=Oliver2005/><ref name=AP19May2009/> The enquiry was told the unit given the order to unload the mortar rounds had received no training for the task.<ref name=AP22May2009/> Meanwhile, 80 drums of fuel were stacked just {{convert|15|ft|m|abbr=on}} from the elevator being used to unload the LCT.<ref name=Oliver2005/>\n\nFollowing testimony, the Naval Enquiry Board concluded that a mortar round exploded on ''LST-353'' sparking a chain reaction. However it could not determine the actual cause of the detonation because all those nearest to the explosion were killed.<ref name=AP19May2009/> This conclusion was sustained by subsequent reviews. The two most plausible explanations were considered to be:\n#the accidental dropping of a mortar round being unloaded from the LCT on the ''LST-353''\n#the ignition of gasoline vapors from high-octane fuel drums stored on the deck of ''LST-353''.<ref name=Oliver2005/><ref name=USNationalParksService27Apr2001/> The source being a cigarette (although banned) or [[welding]], which had also been occurring that day aboard ''LST-353''.<ref name=AP19May2009/>\n\nThe enquiry also heard the conduct of the inexperienced crews may have exacerbated the disaster. [[Lieutenant commander (United States)|Lieutenant Commander]] Joseph B. Hoyt, [[USNR]], the Commander of LST Group 39, Flotilla 13, criticized many of the LST crews for abandoning their vessels too early, leaving them to sink or drift, rather than fire-fighting or attempting to beach them. However he praised the efforts of the crew from ''LST-274'', which received heavy damage but was saved.\nSeveral crews and skippers were called to account for inadequate reactions to the emergency, although the severity of the conditions were cited as mitigating factors.<ref name=Oliver2005/>\n\nIn the end no [[Court-martial|courts-martial]] or [[Letter of reprimand|letters of reprimand]] were issued to anyone involved. The practice of loading fuel and munitions aboard closely moored vessels was deemed to be necessary under the conditions of war and the layout of Pearl Harbor U.S. Navy Base. A recommendation by the Board to avoid nesting in future was criticized by Admiral [[Chester W. Nimitz]] as impractical.<ref name=Oliver2005/><ref name=USNationalParksService27Apr2001/>\n\n==Reporting==\nThe [[United States military]] ordered a [[press blackout]] following the incident. The official inquiry was marked Top Secret and survivors and eyewitnesses were not permitted to mention the incident in letters home.<ref name=Oliver2005/><ref name=DallasMorningNews21May1997/> Four days after the incident, the authorities released a one-paragraph statement noting an explosion had caused \"some loss of life, a number of injuries and resulted in the destruction of several small vessels\". It was only after Operation Forager that a fuller account was released to the press.<ref name=DallasMorningNews21May1997/> The entire incident was not declassified and made public until 1960.<ref name=Oliver2005/>\n\nAs a result of the secrecy surrounding the incident, it has been asserted that the public knows little about Pearl Harbor's \"second disaster\".<ref name=DallasMorningNews21May1997/><ref name= AP22May2009/> As of 1997, the only book about the incident, ''The West Loch Story'', was privately published by survivor, William L.C. Johnson. He alleges that a full account had not emerged from the Navy until 1964, and that the incident had been caused by careless smoking.<ref name=DallasMorningNews21May1997/>\n\n==Impact on Operation Forager==\nSix LSTs were sunk<ref name=Oliver2005/><ref name=USNationalParksService27Apr2001/> (''LST-39'', ''LST-43'', ''LST-69'', ''LST-179'', ''LST-353'', and ''LST-480''),<ref name=\"cressman\"/> two already carrying smaller, fully loaded [[Landing craft tank]]s (''LCT-961'', 963 and 983)<ref name=\"cressman\"/> lashed to their decks.<ref name=Oliver2005/> Several LSTs were damaged and/or ran aground. Four (including LST-205 and LST-225)<ref name=\"cressman\"/> could not be repaired in time for the invasion.<ref name=Oliver2005/> Seventeen tracked landing vehicles (LVT) and eight {{convert|155|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} guns were destroyed.<ref name=\"cressman\"/> Other sources place the total number of destroyed LSTs at nine.<ref name=AP19May2009/> With reinforcement of the fleet from elsewhere, and through quick repair efforts, Operation Forager was only delayed by one day as a result of the incident, with the operation commencing essentially as planned three weeks later.<ref name=Oliver2005/>\n\n==Medal of Honor==\nBoatswain's Mate 2nd Class [[Francis P. Hammerberg]], a Navy diver, posthumously received the [[Medal of Honor]] for heroism on February 17, 1945, during salvage operations on an LST sunk in the West Loch incident.  He was killed in a cave-in while attempting to tunnel under one of the sunken LSTs.  He was the only service member in World War II, and the last person of all, to receive the Medal of Honor for a non-combat action.  (Prior to World War II, the Navy had frequently awarded the Medal of Honor for non-combat heroism.)\n\n==Memorials==\n[[File:US Navy 030521-N-8157C-040 59 years after explosions rang out in Pearl Harbor^rsquo,s West Loch, a memorial of disaster reminds all of a quiet Sunday afternoon on May 21, 1944.jpg|thumb|right|The rusting remains of {{USS|LST-480||2}} at  {{coord|21|21|26.04|N|157|59|50.05|W|scale:10000|display=inline}}.]]\n\nIn the weeks following the disaster, all wreckage was salvaged and removed, with the exception of {{USS|LST-480||2}} (sometimes reported as ''LST-353''<ref name=AP19May2009/>). Its rusting bow was left where it was beached during the disaster.<ref name=Oliver2005/><ref name=USNationalParksService27Apr2001/><ref name= AP22May2009/> In April 1995, the first memorial to the disaster was unveiled: a table-sized plaque sited on the shore of the loch.<ref name=DallasMorningNews21May1997/> At the behest of [[United States Congress|Congress]], gravestones of unidentified victims in the [[National Memorial Cemetery of the Pacific]] were amended in the 2000s (decade) from recording simply \"unknown\", to \"Unknown, West Loch Disaster, May 21, 1944\".<ref name=AP19May2009/> The Navy commemorated the 65th anniversary of the disaster on 21 May 2009.<ref name=AP19May2009/>\n\n==Legacy==\nAs a result of the incident, and the [[Port Chicago disaster]] two months later, the Navy drastically changed its ordnance-handling procedures. It insisted on full training for handlers, munitions to be redesigned for safer handling, and that vessels should no longer be nested together when ammunition was being loaded or handled.<ref name=AP22May2009/>\n\nIt is also possible that the salvage operation undertaken to clear the loch after the disaster inadvertently lengthened the hunt for the \"fifth midget submarine\" involved in the 1941 attack on Pearl Harbor. After three pieces of a midget submarine were discovered three miles south of Pearl Harbor, a working theory was developed that this was the only submarine in a group of five Japanese [[Ko-hyoteki class submarine]]s involved in the attack that had not yet been accounted for. Researchers posited that it had penetrated the harbor to attack [[Battleship Row]], before escaping into West Loch and being scuttled by the two-man crew. Lying on the bed of the loch, it was then salvaged along with the remains of the LSTs, LCTs and landing tanks, and then dumped at sea.<ref name=LATimes7Dec2009/><ref name=NovaTranscript/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of accidents and disasters by death toll#Explosions|List of accidents and disasters by death toll, explosions]]\n*[[List of accidents and incidents involving transport or storage of ammunition]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"cressman\">{{cite book|title=The Official Chronology of the U.S. Navy in World War II|author=Cressman, Robert J.|publisher=Naval Institute Press|year=2000|isbn=1-55750-149-1|page=[https://archive.org/details/TheOfficialChronologyOfTheUSNavyInWorldWarII/page/229 229]|url=https://archive.org/details/TheOfficialChronologyOfTheUSNavyInWorldWarII/page/229}}</ref><ref name=NovaTranscript>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/nova/transcripts/3701_killersubs.html \n |title=Killer Subs in Pearl Harbour \n |publisher=PBS \n |work=Transcript, Nova \n |date=5 January 2010 \n |accessdate=12 April 2010 \n |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5owWRjeJv?url=http://www.pbs.org/wgbh/nova/transcripts/3701_killersubs.html \n |archivedate=12 April 2010 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref><ref name=LATimes7Dec2009>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/nation-and-world/la-sci-minisub7-2009dec07,0,6991792.story |title=Pearl Harbor mini-submarine mystery solved? |publisher=LA Times |date=7 December 2009 |accessdate=12 April 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5owWR6r8n?url=http://www.latimes.com/news/nation-and-world/la-sci-minisub7-2009dec07%2C0%2C6991792.story |archivedate=12 April 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=Oliver2005>{{cite web|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qa4442/is_200511/ai_n16059243/|title=Navy's hushed up tragedy at West Loch|publisher=Challenge Publications|work=Sea Classics magazine|author=Oliver, A Alan|date=November 2005|accessdate=12 April 2010}}</ref><ref name=USNationalParksService27Apr2001>{{cite web|url=http://www.nps.gov/archive/usar/scrs/scrs2z.htm |title=West Loch disaster |work=Submerged Cultural Resources Study:USS Arizona and Pearl Harbor National Historic Landmark, Chapter II: Historical Record |publisher=US National Park Service |date=27 April 2001 |accessdate=12 April 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5owIMj68d?url=http://www.nps.gov/archive/usar/scrs/scrs2z.htm |archivedate=12 April 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=AP19May2009>{{cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/wirestory?id=7621375&page=1 |title=Navy Recalls Bravery at WWII's West Loch Disaster |publisher=ABC News / Associated Press |date=19 May 2009 |accessdate=12 April 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5owIsa8VQ?url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/wirestory?id=7621375 |archivedate=12 April 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=AP22May2009>{{cite news|url=http://www.armytimes.com/news/2009/05/ap_west_loch_disaster_052109/ |title=Deadly 1944 Pearl Harbor disaster remembered |publisher=Army Times / Associated Press |date=2 May 2009 |accessdate=12 April 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5owRwkfl9?url=http://www.armytimes.com/news/2009/05/ap_west_loch_disaster_052109/ |archivedate=12 April 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=DallasMorningNews21May1997>{{cite news|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19970521&slug=2540393 |title=Second Tragedy at Pearl Harbor Is Little-Known |publisher=Dallas Morning News |date=21 May 1997 |accessdate=12 April 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5owLF9bbi?url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19970521 |archivedate=12 April 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>}}\n\n[[Category:Explosions in 1944]]\n[[Category:Industrial fires and explosions in the United States]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in May 1944]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in the United States]]\n[[Category:United States Navy in the 20th century]]\n[[Category:History of Oahu]]\n[[Category:Ship fires]]\n[[Category:Non-combat internal explosions on warships]]\n[[Category:1944 in Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Transportation disasters in Hawaii]]\n", "name_user": "DulcetTone", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixing bad edit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/West_Loch_disaster"}
